entry.title: Prerender: Use PrerenderWebContentsDelegate as default impl in content/

entry.title: Update webIDL to support close event.
entry.content:
We supported a MessagePort close event, which is behind a flag now and added a test to check

if this event is enabled.

I added a new virtual expectations file(global-interface-listing-audio-worklet-expected.txt).

This is because the test harness uses the non-virtual expectations in testing virtual test

if there are no virtual expectations.

However, The non-virtual version expects onclose, while the virtual version does not.

So, I added the virtual expectations file so that the test harness uses the virtual version

expected.txt in testing the virtual test.

entry.title: Dismissible issues / errors messages in Harmony
entry.content:
This issue appeared after the change of Harmony dialog to have a stop button.



Beforehand, to be able to terminate the session, the user has to click on the sink name, and if it has an issue (error message), the message would be dismissed and then the user would have to re-click on the sink name to terminate the session.





After the UI changes to use a stop button, sink name and its error messages are no longer clickable, they are just labels. So, the user has no way to dismiss the error message as long as the session is active.



This CL fixes that issue.

entry.title: [rebaseline-cl] Do not fill in results for ports that skip tests
entry.content:
`rebaseline-cl` has a feature to substitute incomplete results with

those from other ports. However, intentionally skipped tests are

incorrectly treated as "missing", which causes `rebaseline-cl` to

download and leave behind baselines for those skipped ports (because the

optimizer ignores skipped tests).



Also, use `Port.operating_system()` instead of parsing the raw port name

to determine OS family (e.g., `mac-mac12-arm64` incorrectly parsed as OS

`mac-mac12` instead of `mac`).



This issue became more apparent after reducing tests run on mac10.15

(crrev.com/c/4967713).

been abandoned.

entry.title: Fix some UBSan errors in Blink
entry.content:
ConvertTimingForCompositor needs to be called later because otherwise

it calls a method on a null timeline_.



Likewise, target_ in PerformanceEventTiming seems to sometimes be null.



Finally, memcpy is obnoxious and, due to a C language bug, is UB when

passed null, 0, despite (null, 0) being a perfectly reasonable

representation of the empty span. A default-constructed std::vector

will give a null data() pointer. C++ STL functions all handle this fine,

but memcpy in C++ inherits the C bug. See also

https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/49459 and

https://www.imperialviolet.org/2016/06/26/nonnull.html for how much of

a mess this is.

entry.title: Initialize CoderErrorMgr when decoding JPEGs.
entry.content:
Initialize CoderErrorMgr when decoding JPEGs.



gfx::JPEGCodec::Decode() creates an uninitialized `CoderErrorMsg`, which

contains a `jpeg_error_mgr`, which contains a `msg_parm` union. This

union is used much later inside libjpeg_turbo:



// From third_party/libjpeg_turbo/jerror.c:175:

SNPRINTF(buffer, JMSG_LENGTH_MAX, msgtext,

err->msg_parm.i[0], err->msg_parm.i[1],

err->msg_parm.i[2], err->msg_parm.i[3],

err->msg_parm.i[4], err->msg_parm.i[5],

err->msg_parm.i[6], err->msg_parm.i[7]);



libjpeg_turbo only initializes as many `msg_parm.i` entries as the

corresponding format specifier consumes, relying on `SNPRINTF()` to

ignore extra arguments. However, MSan still warns that this is a use of

an uninitialized value, and indeed, the C standard says:



If the format is exhausted while arguments remain, the excess

arguments are evaluated (as always) but are otherwise ignored.



Bug: 1369167

Change-Id: I35ac2bf7eecea6152d765de2015261f33cbe6615

Reviewed-on: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5008686

Reviewed-by: Leon Scroggins

Commit-Queue: Daniel Cheng

Cr-Commit-Position: refs/heads/main@{#1221255}

entry.title: Fix Mp4MuxerBoxWriterTest tests with -fsanitize-memory-param-retval.
entry.content:
With this flag, msan uses stricter checks that better match the

standard, which states in [basic.indet]/2 that "If an indeterminate

value is produced by an evaluation, the behavior is undefined", with

limited exceptions for unsigned char and std::byte values. An important

side effect is this makes C++ ABI compatibler with Rust when building

with msan support.



This means code like the following is no longer accepted:



void F(int) {}

void G() {

int uninitialized;

// use-of-uninitialized-value here when calling F().

F(uninitialized);

}



The various box writers cause msan errors when writing out uninitialized

fields. The solution is to use in-class initializers to assign default

values for various integer type fields rather than allowing them to

remain uninitialized.

entry.title: [OOPIF PDF] Allow PDF resource requests for PDF navigation
entry.content:
Allow PDF extension resources to be requested only for the frames in the

PDF Viewer architecture. The frames that should be able to access the

resources are the extension frame and the content frame.



In ResourceRequestPolicy::CanRequestResource(), if the top frame has the

same origin as the resource, then the resource can be requested. This is

the case for MimeHandlerViewGuest PDF Viewer, as the PDF extension is in

an inner WebContents.



For OOPIF PDF Viewer, there is only one WebContents, so the top frame's

origin is not the same. Loosen the conditions to allow PDF resource

requests for OOPIF PDF Viewer.
